<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/68D0E3C9-9246-4CFC-B5E9-48584CF82993"><gtr:id>68D0E3C9-9246-4CFC-B5E9-48584CF82993</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Manchester</gtr:name><gtr:department>Environment, Education and Development</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Oxford Road</gtr:line1><gtr:city>Manchester</gtr:city><gtr:postCode>M13 9PL</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>North West</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/68D0E3C9-9246-4CFC-B5E9-48584CF82993"><gtr:id>68D0E3C9-9246-4CFC-B5E9-48584CF82993</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Manchester</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Oxford Road</gtr:line1><gtr:city>Manchester</gtr:city><gtr:postCode>M13 9PL</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>North West</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/17AD4CD0-A8D6-43E0-A6CF-3308F3B4BD7F"><gtr:id>17AD4CD0-A8D6-43E0-A6CF-3308F3B4BD7F</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Jessica</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Budds</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>RESEARCHER</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=PTA-026-27-0854"><gtr:id>3D01F405-53B5-4728-8A3B-512AFCC65C0B</gtr:id><gtr:title>The Political Ecology of Water and Uneven Development in Latin America</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>PTA-026-27-0854</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This research explores issues of uneven social and geographical development in Latin America through the lens of water. This work adopts an interdisciplinary approach between the social and natural sciences that weaves between the material and social dimensions of water. This entails both a critical engagement with the environmental sciences, to examine how scientific knowledge is used to underpin environmental management, and political ecology theories, to reveal the underlying power structures embedded within water management and their uneven socio-ecological outcomes.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>The empirical research focuses on socio-ecological conflicts over water in Chile and Peru, using qualitative (unstructured interviews, documentation) and quantitative (surveys, hydrology, geology) methods. In Chile, research on the politicisation of water management at the national level and struggles between commercial and peasant farmers will be complemented with a case on competition over water between indigenous groups, the mining industry and wetlands.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/p>

&lt;p>Here, the focus lies on understanding the differential socio-ecological outcomes of water management for different social groups, how these are articulated in terms of livelihoods, environmental management, national economic development and ?Chilean? identity, and the roles of scientific information and local knowledge. These questions will form the basis of further research on water and mining in Peru.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2006-12-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-01-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>30664</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>01FF833A-20E0-4705-B44E-C44165829A93</gtr:id><gtr:title>Water, Power, and the Production of Neoliberalism in Chile, 1973-2005</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Environment and Planning D: Society and Space</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/6e363df3d04e5a5d59453a98e1ef538a"><gtr:id>6e363df3d04e5a5d59453a98e1ef538a</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Budds J</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2013-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>m_2323840953135e1740</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>12E150FE-D123-498C-AA26-20CA10F35703</gtr:id><gtr:title>Mapping Latin America: A Cartographic Reader</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/